Subject Stages argues that the discourses and practices of marital legislation, litigation, and theatrics informed each other during this period in ways that still have a critical bearing on contemporary events in Spain, such as the legalization of divorce in 1978 and of same-sex marriage in 2005. Carrión's comprehensive and clear analysis pulls back the facade of the 'happily ever after' marriage plot on stage to reveal the inner workings of the legal, economic, political, and social networks that mainstream theatre was able to critique.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLaw and literaturezSpainxHistory. 0aMarriage in literature. 0aMarriage lawzSpainxHistoryy16th century. 0aMarriage lawzSpainxHistoryy17th century. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268651940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442686519423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442686519.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK